name: DJ Shouting at Music Festival
description:
For my radio drama, I needed a "dubstep cover of a Beatles song" but that would have cost almost a thousand dollars. In lieu of that, I just made the sounds of a DJ introducing said Dubstep cover. This vocal was recorded at Strawberry Fields in Colorado Springs, which is a once-public-but-now-private park, and hasn't really been manipulated in anyway. It's just me saying things like "Make some motherfucking noise" and talking to an imaginary crowd in a very loud voice. I figured since I couldn't find something like this on Freesound and had to make it myself, I would share it with you folks so that, if you ever find yourself in the same extremely specific predicament (or just need someone shouting) you can use this clip so you don't have to go to a park and bother the hikers. 

If you use it, you can credit "Timmy Vilgiate"

name: Uyoku_shouting.WAV
description:
This is a recording of an "Uyoku" truck in Tokyo.
These are big, black trucks with massive old-school cone shaped PA speakers on the roof, they drive around Tokyo shouting distorted nationalistic messages.
This one was parked in the middle of large road junction in Roppongi, Tokyo, near the Ferrari showroom.

name: voice_overs_by_braille'n_speak.wav
description:
Braille'n speak is a notetaker for blind people with Braille input and speech output. The development of this product was discontinued. This is an example of Speech synthesis speaking some useful voice overs:
in the mix
ladies and gentleman
let's dance
and now, the drop
close your eyes and open your ears
let's go
get ready
we wish you a marry Christmas and happy new year
hello world
the best music
that's all
There are two voices. Both are with voice inflection. I recorded it via Line in and converted to mono, as original output was only in one channel. The noise is generated by the unit. You can reduce it via some expander, or the Audacity noise reduction works very well (I gave an extra space at the end of recording as the noise profile).

Note that this might work best layered with music, to help mask this fact.)
